{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01F2PvwhNy8NpP4xGsRhUVTh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from recommendation results regardless of relevance score.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about filtering logic — one function checking availability. This could be unit tested if it's a pure filter function.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed. Catalog data could be in-memory.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Could mock the product catalog and verify filtering logic.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM dependency here. The filtering is deterministic.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\n\n- The core question is whether the filter correctly excludes out-of-stock items, which is fundamentally a unit-level concern if the filter is a pure function. Even if it interacts with the catalog repository and ranking module, the behavior itself is deterministic and testable at the unit level.\n\n**Behavior 2: User preference filter correctly excludes product categories the user has explicitly blocked.**\n\nThis is another deterministic filter based on user settings. The failure mode is straightforward — the filter doesn't properly exclude blocked categories. I can test this at the unit level by providing products with categories, a set of blocked categories, and verifying the filter removes the right ones.\n\nUnit level.\n\n**Behavior 3: Recommendation algorithm ranks products matching recent browsing patterns higher.**\n\nThis involves the ranking algorithm's logic and needs browsing history data plus product scoring. The real question is whether this is a deterministic algorithm like collaborative filtering with fixed weights, or something LLM-based or ML-dependent that requires mocking external models.\n\nThe description mentions \"weighs purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior\" — that sounds like a traditional recommender system, not an LLM. So I can test it deterministically with mocked data. The interaction between retrieving browsing history and applying it to rankings happens at module boundaries, which suggests integration testing is the right level.\n\n**Behavior 4: Pagination returns correct page, stable ordering when data hasn't changed.**\n\nFor pagination and ordering stability, I need to verify that requesting the same page twice produces identical results. This is testing whether the ranking and sorting are deterministic. Since pagination and ranking work together to produce stable output, this feels like an integration test between those two modules.\n\n**Behavior 5: Algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category the user hasn't browsed (serendipity).**\n\nThis is testing the recommendation algorithm's serendipity feature.\n\nThe algorithm needs to have this behavior built in. If it's a traditional deterministic recommender rather than LLM-based, I can test this at the integration level by setting up controlled input data with the catalog, user profile, and recommendation engine all wired together to verify the diversity constraint is satisfied.\n\n**Behavior 6: New user with no history receives popularity-based recommendations, not empty results.**\n\nThe cold-start handling is what matters here — the failure mode would be returning nothing instead of falling back to popularity-based rankings. Since there's no LLM and popularity ranking is deterministic, this is an integration test that needs the user profile lookup connected to the recommendation engine.\n\n**Behavior 7: Click tracking records correct product ID, position, and timestamp.**\n\nThe tracking service needs to write the right data to storage. I don't need a real database for this — an in-memory store is sufficient to verify the data is being recorded correctly, so this stays at integration level where the tracking service interacts with the storage layer.\n\n**Behavior 8: Response time under 200ms for 100,000 product catalog.**\n\nThis one actually requires real infrastructure. I can't get meaningful performance numbers with stubs and in-memory stores — I need a real database and real computation to test whether the system can handle 100k products within the latency constraint. This is a system-level test.\n\n**Behavior 9: After purchase, recommendation algorithm deprioritizes that product.**\n\nThe purchase event system, recommendation algorithm, and product scoring need to work together correctly. No LLM involved if it's a traditional algorithm, and no real infrastructure needed. This is integration level.\n\n**Behavior 10: Recommendation results are deterministic for the same user state.**\n\nI'm checking whether the full recommendation pipeline produces consistent results — this could reveal non-determinism from things like random tie-breaking or timestamp variations. If it's a traditional algorithm, it should be deterministic without needing real infrastructure.\n\nLooking back at the issue description, it mentions the algorithm \"weighs purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior to rank products,\" which sounds like a traditional collaborative filtering or matrix factorization approach rather than an LLM-based system. That means these behaviors should stay at integration level — I can test them with controlled datasets and expect deterministic outputs. No agentic-level testing needed.\n\nLet me finalize my categorization: out-of-stock filtering is unit-level pure logic, user preference filtering is also unit-level, browsing patterns ranking requires the recommendation engine to interact with historical data so that's integration, pagination stability needs ranking and pagination modules working together which is integration, serendipity requires the full catalog and user profile feeding into the engine so integration, cold-start scenarios need profile lookup and fallback logic interacting which is integration, click tracking involves the tracking service and storage layer so integration, response time testing needs real infrastructure with actual catalog data which is system-level, post-purchase deprioritization requires the purchase event to flow through the ranking algorithm so integration, and deterministic results need the full pipeline running consistently which is integration. , Agentic 0.03, Workflow 0.01. For the remaining behaviors, I'm assigning integration-level tests across the board. Browsing pattern ranking needs the full recommendation pipeline to validate ranking quality, pagination stability requires integration to ensure consistent ordering across requests, serendipity testing demands the algorithm's actual output to measure diversity, and cold-start scenarios need the integrated system to properly handle new user data flows. The probabilities reflect varying confidence—pagination and cold-start are more clearly integration tests, while browsing patterns and serendipity have higher agentic components since they involve more complex behavioral validation.\n\nNow I'm looking at the remaining test cases. Click tracking is integration-heavy since it needs the full pipeline to verify event capture and ranking feedback loops. Response time is clearly system-level—that's pure infrastructure performance. Post-purchase deprioritization requires integration to test how the algorithm adjusts rankings after purchase events. Deterministic results also needs integration to validate the algorithm's consistency.\n\nActually, let me reconsider a few of these with the LLM dependency question in mind. The recommendation engine uses an algorithm that weighs purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior—this could be a traditional ML model like collaborative filtering or a neural network, which would change how I categorize some of these tests.\n\nThe real question is whether correctness depends on what an actual trained ML model produces. If it's using a real ML model, then the browsing pattern ranking and serendipity behaviors would be agentic since they depend on the model's output quality. Post-purchase deprioritization might still be integration if it's an explicit rule applied on top of the model. And determinism becomes agentic if the ML model has any randomness built in. But the issue just says \"recommendation algorithm\" without specifying whether it's LLM-based or a traditional ML approach. I'm realizing there's a potential tension between behavior 5 (serendipity requiring diversity) and behavior 10 (determinism requiring consistent outputs)—if serendipity involves randomness, how can the results be deterministic? This is a key constraint I need to resolve in my analysis.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9697,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9697},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d8a8201-6197-435a-bb22-610f2ac644df","uuid":"c792977d-d01d-4b52-be5d-7181769509ea"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01F2PvwhNy8NpP4xGsRhUVTh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Qr289X8R3aytSkQibW3UkH","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Out-of-stock products excluded from recommendations regardless of relevance score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a logic bug in the availability filter — a product with a high relevance score passes through when it should be blocked. This is a single function boundary: given a list of (product, score) pairs and an availability predicate, the output must contain no unavailable products. No module handoff is required to expose this bug. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed; in-memory product stubs suffice. LLM-DEP: Filtering is deterministic. REJECTION-GATE: Integration would require the ranking engine to also be wired in; the behavior text ('excluded from recommendation results regardless of relevance score') describes the filter function's own invariant, not a cross-module handoff failure.","test_description":"Construct a list of products with mixed availability and pre-assigned relevance scores, where the highest-scoring product is out-of-stock. Pass the list through the availability filter and assert that the output contains zero out-of-stock products and that all in-stock products with their original scores are present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.62,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"User preference filter correctly excludes explicitly blocked product categories.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a logic bug in the preference filter function: a product whose category is in the user's blocked list is returned anyway. This is a pure function (blocked_categories × product_catalog → filtered_catalog) with no module handoff needed to expose the bug. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/DB needed. LLM-DEP: Deterministic. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior text describes a filter predicate's correctness, not an interaction between the preference store and the filtering pipeline; escalating to Integration is unwarranted unless the behavior described a failure at that boundary.","test_description":"Create a user settings object with two blocked categories and a product list spanning three categories (one of which is double-blocked). Pass through the preference filter and assert: (a) all products in blocked categories are absent, (b) all products in the allowed category are present, (c) no products are duplicated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Recommendation algorithm ranks products matching recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure only appears when the browsing history data pipeline and the ranking scorer are wired together — a unit test of the scorer alone with hardcoded inputs cannot verify that real browsing history signals are correctly retrieved and weighted. The bug is at the handoff between the browsing history repository and the ranking function. REAL-INFRA: No real network/OS needed; an in-process fake browsing store suffices. LLM-DEP: The description ('weighs purchase history, browsing patterns') describes a traditional algorithmic/statistical recommender, not an LLM; the ranking is deterministic given fixed inputs. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: no text indicates a real ML/AI model call whose output quality must be validated; the behavior tests that browsing signals are consumed and applied correctly, which a deterministic algorithm handles.","test_description":"Wire a fake browsing history store (user has viewed products A and B in category X) to the recommendation engine with a controlled product catalog. Run recommendations and assert that products in category X with browsing signal appear ranked above products in category Y with no browsing signal. Vary the number of browsing events and confirm ranking shifts accordingly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.28,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns the correct page with stable ordering when underlying data hasn't changed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Ordering instability typically emerges at the boundary between the ranking engine (which produces a scored list) and the pagination layer (which slices it). A unit test of the slicer alone with a pre-sorted list cannot detect non-determinism introduced upstream. The failure needs both modules to hand off. REAL-INFRA: No real DB needed; in-memory state captures the invariant. LLM-DEP: Pagination + sorting are deterministic. REJECTION-GATE for System: no real network or OS filesystem events are required; in-process fake data reproduces the failure.","test_description":"Seed the recommendation engine with a fixed user state and catalog. Request page 2 twice consecutively with no intervening mutations. Assert the two responses are byte-identical (same product IDs in the same order). Also assert page 2 contains a disjoint set from page 1 and that page_size items are returned.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Recommendation algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category the user hasn't browsed (serendipity requirement).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The serendipity constraint requires the browsing history store, the product catalog, and the diversity-injection component to cooperate. A unit test of diversity logic with hardcoded category lists cannot verify that unexplored categories are correctly derived from the live browsing profile. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. LLM-DEP: Described as an explicit algorithmic diversity requirement, not a quality judgment that only a real ML model can make. The assertion is structural (at least one unvisited category present), not a quality assessment of recommendations. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: the behavior tests a hard constraint enforced by code, not an emergent quality property of an AI model.","test_description":"Set up a user profile with browsing history covering exactly two categories. Configure a catalog with products in four categories. Run the recommendation engine and assert that the result set contains at least one product whose category does not appear in the user's browsing history. Repeat with the user profile covering all-but-one category to verify the constraint still holds at the boundary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.27,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"New user with no purchase or browsing history receives popularity-based recommendations, not an empty result set.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The cold-start failure is a missing or broken fallback path triggered only when the user profile lookup returns empty history. The bug appears at the handoff between the profile store (returning null/empty) and the ranking engine (failing to fall back to popularity). A unit test with a hardcoded empty profile list misses failures in how the engine reacts to the empty signal from the real profile loader. REAL-INFRA: No real DB needed; a stub profile store returning an empty record suffices. LLM-DEP: Popularity ranking is deterministic (e.g., aggregate sales counts). REJECTION-GATE for System: no OS/network primitives required.","test_description":"Wire a stub user profile store that returns no purchase or browsing history for a new user ID. Inject a catalog with known popularity scores. Run recommendations and assert: (a) the result set is non-empty, (b) all returned products are ordered by descending popularity score, (c) no products from a personalised-signal path appear in the ranking.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records correct product ID, position in list, and timestamp for each recommendation interaction.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is incorrect data written to the tracking store — wrong product ID, wrong position index (off-by-one), or missing/wrong timestamp. This only manifests when the click event handler (which receives a click event with a product ID and list context) and the tracking store (which persists the record) are wired together. A unit test of the event handler alone with a mock store cannot verify the stored record's shape. REAL-INFRA: A real database is not required; an in-memory tracking store or a captured-write spy catches the failure. LLM-DEP: Tracking is deterministic. REJECTION-GATE for System: no real network/OS events required to expose incorrect field mapping.","test_description":"Seed the recommendation engine with a known result list of five products. Simulate a click event on the third product. Assert the tracking store received exactly one record with: product_id matching the third product, position=3 (or 2 if 0-indexed, per spec), and timestamp within an acceptable window of now. Then simulate two more clicks and assert three records in total with correct positions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Response time for generating recommendations stays under 200ms for a catalog of 100,000 products.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Latency under real load is the only meaningful measurement here. An in-process fake catalog of 100k items cannot reproduce I/O latency, memory pressure, serialization cost, or query planning behavior against a real data store. The failure — exceeding 200ms — only appears under real infrastructure with a real-sized dataset. MOCK-HIDE: A stub catalog always returns instantly, making this test vacuously pass and hiding every real performance bottleneck. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: the behavior text specifies 'a catalog of 100,000 products,' which requires real infrastructure to populate and query; an in-process fake would not expose real algorithmic or I/O scaling behavior.","test_description":"Provision a test catalog with 100,000 products in a real database (or populated in-memory structure exercising real query/sort paths). Execute the recommendation pipeline end-to-end for a representative user profile. Capture wall-clock time from request to fully-serialized response. Assert p99 latency < 200ms across N repeated calls. Run against both cold-cache and warm-cache scenarios.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.82,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"When a recommended product is purchased, the recommendation algorithm deprioritizes it in subsequent requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the handoff between the purchase event pipeline (writing to purchase history) and the ranking engine (reading and applying the deprioritization rule). A unit test of the ranker with a hardcoded purchased-product list cannot detect failures where the purchase event is not correctly persisted or retrieved before the next recommendation call. REAL-INFRA: No real network/OS needed; an in-process fake purchase store captures the cross-module handoff. LLM-DEP: The deprioritization rule ('products the user has bought rank lower') is a deterministic signal applied to a traditional recommender. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: the behavior tests that a specific signal is correctly applied, not the quality of AI-generated rankings.","test_description":"Seed the recommendation engine with a user profile where product X has a high relevance score and has not been purchased. Capture the initial recommendation ranking (X appears near top). Simulate a purchase event for product X, flushing it to the fake purchase history store. Re-run recommendations and assert that product X's rank is lower than in the initial response, and lower than at least one product with equivalent relevance score but no purchase history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Recommendation results are deterministic for the same user state — two consecutive requests with no intervening activity return identical ranked lists.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Non-determinism typically originates deep in the pipeline — hash-map iteration order, un-seeded random tie-breaking, timestamp-seeded shuffles for serendipity, or race conditions between components. These only appear when the full wired pipeline runs end-to-end with real module interactions. A unit test with a controlled scorer cannot expose non-determinism injected by other modules. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed; an in-process stack is sufficient to expose determinism failures. LLM-DEP: The system is described as a traditional weighing algorithm; if it used a real LLM the test would always fail (Agentic), but the behavior asserts determinism is expected, implying the system is designed to be deterministic. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: the behavior requires determinism, which disqualifies using a real LLM (whose outputs are non-deterministic); this test validates the algorithmic pipeline's determinism, not LLM output quality.","test_description":"Fix a user state (profile, browsing history, purchase history) and catalog snapshot. Execute the recommendation pipeline twice with identical inputs and no mutations between calls. Assert the two result lists are identical in length, product IDs, and rank order. Run this assertion across at least three distinct user profiles (new user, moderate history, heavy history) to cover different algorithm branches.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.22,"Workflow":0.04}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9697,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9697},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d8a8201-6197-435a-bb22-610f2ac644df","uuid":"adaf9de0-dd23-4fe5-8a0c-5b684f79fad3"}
